   at /images/og/standards-common-ground.png (generated by scripts/generate-og.js
   on the next push to main; falls back to og-default.png until then). #}
{% block og_title %}Common Ground: an open standard for sovereign Indigenous data platforms{% endblock %}
{% block og_description %}A shared way for sovereign First Nations platforms to exchange data, enforce each Nation's rules, and prove it. OIATC is starting it now and inviting Nations, builders, and partners to help define it.{% endblock %}

{% block head_styles %}
  {% include 'partials/funder-styles.html.twig' %}
  <style>
    /* Common Ground open call. Built on the site shell's numbered-section style
       (.sec / .sec__head), with a few namespaced .cg-* helpers for the hero
       tagline, the running prose measure, and the CTA note. */
    .route-standards-common-ground h1.display { font-size: clamp(32px, 4.4vw, 58px); line-height: 1.06; }
    .cg-tagline { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent-deep); margin: var(--gap-5) 0 0; }
    .cg-body { max-width: 72ch; }
    .cg-body p { font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--ink-2); margin: 0 0 var(--gap-4); }
    .cg-body p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .cg-body strong { color: var(--ink); font-weight: 600; }
    .cg-after { margin-top: var(--gap-5); }
    .cg-note { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--ink-3); margin: var(--gap-4) 0 0; }
  </style>
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
    <section class="masthead">
      <div class="shell">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Common Ground · Open call</div>
          <h1 class="display">First Nations are building their own data platforms, one at a time. None of them can work together yet.</h1>
          <p class="cg-tagline">Protocol before product. Consent before architecture.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="lede">Common Ground is an open standard to change that: a shared way for sovereign platforms to exchange data, enforce each Nation's rules, and prove they follow them. OIATC is starting it now and inviting Nations, builders, and partners to help define it. This is a starting point for a shared effort, not a finished proposal.</p>
          <div class="masthead__facts">
            <dl>
              <dt>Status</dt><dd>Open call, early draft</dd>
              <dt>Builds on</dt><dd>CARE, OCAP, IEEE 2890</dd>
              <dt>Seeking</dt><dd>Nations, builders, governance partners</dd>
              <dt>Published</dt><dd>June 2026</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sec" id="gap">
      <div class="shell">
        <div class="sec__head reveal">
          <div><div class="sec__num">01 · The gap</div></div>
          <div>
            <h2 class="sec__title">The principles exist. The way to enforce them across platforms does not.</h2>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cg-body reveal">
          <p>The hard part is not deciding the rules. <strong>CARE</strong> and <strong>OCAP</strong> already set out who decides and on what terms. As of November 2025 there is also a first global technical standard, <strong>IEEE 2890</strong>, for recording where Indigenous data came from. These are real foundations, and Common Ground builds on them. It does not replace them.</p>
          <p>What none of them provide is the next layer up. IEEE 2890 makes the description of data shareable, so two systems can read where data came from. It does not make one platform enforce another community's consent rules when data crosses between them, and it gives no way to certify that a platform actually does what it claims. That layer, <strong>enforcement across platforms and a way to prove conformance</strong>, is missing. No standard has claimed it.</p>
          <p>The result is that every new sovereign platform risks becoming a sovereign silo. All built on the same mission, none able to safely connect, and no Nation able to verify that a tool it did not build can be trusted. Today every vendor self-asserts that it respects OCAP, and nobody can check.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sec" id="what-it-does">
      <div class="shell">
        <div class="sec__head reveal">
          <div><div class="sec__num">02 · What the standard would do</div></div>
          <div>
            <h2 class="sec__title">Let platforms share, enforce each Nation's rules, and prove it.</h2>
            <p class="sec__intro">Common Ground is a thin layer on top of what already exists. It does not rewrite CARE, OCAP, or IEEE 2890, and it does not reinvent the general machinery for sharing data between systems, which is already proven elsewhere. It binds those pieces into something a machine can act on and a Nation can verify. Three jobs.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="grid-3 reveal">
          <article class="card">
            <div class="card__eyebrow">01 / Interoperate</div>
            <h3>Share, or ask without moving</h3>
            <p class="body">A shared way for two platforms to exchange data, or to run a question against data that never leaves the community that holds it.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <div class="card__eyebrow">02 / Enforce</div>
            <h3>Rules software follows</h3>
            <p class="body">A community's permissions become rules that software follows. Consent, refusal, and the right to withdraw are honoured when data moves between platforms, not just written down on paper.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <div class="card__eyebrow">03 / Certify</div>
            <h3>Proof, not a sales pitch</h3>
            <p class="body">A test any platform can be measured against, so a Nation can ask for proof of conformance instead of trusting a sales pitch.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sec" id="principles">
      <div class="shell">
        <div class="sec__head reveal">
          <div><div class="sec__num">03 · The principles this effort holds to</div></div>
          <div>
            <h2 class="sec__title">The standard is governed the way the data should be.</h2>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="principles reveal">
          <div class="principles__item">
            <div class="principles__num">01</div>
            <h3 class="principles__t">Indigenous-governed</h3>
            <p class="principles__b">Authority over the standard rests with Indigenous participants, not with any one company or platform. Vendors implement the standard. They do not own it.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="principles__item">
            <div class="principles__num">02</div>
            <h3 class="principles__t">Open and free to implement</h3>
            <p class="principles__b">No license fees, no gatekeeping, so cost is never a barrier for a small Nation or a small builder.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="principles__item">
            <div class="principles__num">03</div>
            <h3 class="principles__t">Distinctions-based</h3>
            <p class="principles__b">Designed to serve First Nations and to interoperate with Metis and Inuit efforts, never to absorb them. Each Nation is the authority over its own data.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="principles__item">
            <div class="principles__num">04</div>
            <h3 class="principles__t">Built on what exists</h3>
            <p class="principles__b">It aligns with CARE, OCAP, and IEEE 2890, and works with the people and bodies already doing this work rather than around them.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sec" id="who">
      <div class="shell">
        <div class="sec__head reveal">
          <div><div class="sec__num">04 · Who this is for</div></div>
          <div>
            <h2 class="sec__title">It will take Nations, builders, and hard questions, not only engineers.</h2>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal">
          <ul class="fund-list">
            <li><strong>First Nations, their councils and data staff</strong>, especially those standing up or planning their own data centres and platforms.</li>
            <li><strong>Builders and platforms</strong> already working on sovereign Indigenous data and AI tools, including those who would implement and test the standard first.</li>
            <li><strong>Organizations and networks</strong> holding governance expertise, including those connected to CARE, OCAP, IEEE 2890, and the regional data governance work underway across the country.</li>
            <li><strong>Researchers and practitioners</strong> in Indigenous data governance, federated data, and AI safety.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="cg-body cg-after">
            <p>You do not need to be a technical person to take part. Governance, lived community experience, and plain hard questions are as valuable as engineering.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sec" id="take-part">
      <div class="shell">
        <div class="sec__head reveal">
          <div><div class="sec__num">05 · How to take part</div></div>
          <div>
            <h2 class="sec__title">Get in while the scope is still open.</h2>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cg-body reveal">
          <p>This is the beginning. The first step is to gather the people who want to define this together, compare what each of us is already building, and agree on a first scope. The earlier you join, the more you shape.</p>
          <p>If you want in, get in touch with OIATC. Tell us who you are, what you are building or governing, and what you would want a standard like this to protect.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="actions reveal">
          <a class="btn btn--primary" href="mailto:jonesrussell42@gmail.com">Write to OIATC &rarr;</a>
          <a class="btn btn--secondary" href="/support">Partner with OIATC</a>
        </div>
        <p class="cg-note reveal">One seat is held by the founder. Writing to Russell is writing to OIATC.</p>

        <div class="fund-more reveal">
          <p class="fund-more__k">Related work from OIATC</p>
          <div class="fund-more__links">
            <a href="/programs/anokii">Anokii: sovereign community infrastructure</a>
            <a href="/positions/sovereign-ai">When a foreign order can switch off your AI</a>
            <a href="/explainers/where-your-data-lives">Where your data lives</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="fund-byline reveal">Common Ground is a community effort convened by OIATC, the Ontario Indigenous AI and Technology Council. OIATC is independent and nonpartisan, and is not FNIGC. This is an open invitation, and the shape of the standard is for the participants to decide together. Published June 2026.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
{% endblock %}
